Absolute value">absolute value</a> of the complex number, while the angle f=
rom the positive real axis is called the argument of the complex number. Th=
e complex numbers of absolute value one form the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Unit_circle" title=3D"Unit circle">unit circle</a>. Adding a=
 fixed complex number to all complex numbers defines a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Translation_(geometry)" title=3D"Translation (geometry=
)">translation</a> in the complex plane, and multiplying by a fixed complex=
 number is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Similarity_(geometry)=
" title=3D"Similarity (geometry)">similarity</a> centered at the origin (di=
lating by the absolute value, and rotating by the argument). The operation =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_conjugation" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Complex conjugation">complex conjugation</a> is the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reflection_symmetry" title=3D"Reflec=
tion symmetry">reflection symmetry</a> with respect to the real axis.=20
</p><p>The complex numbers form a rich structure that is simultaneously an =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraically_closed_field" title=
=3D"Algebraically closed field">algebraically closed field</a>, a <a href=
