            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>i</mi>
        <mo>=E2=8B=85<!-- =E2=8B=85 --></mo>
        <mi>i</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mn>1.</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle i^{2}=3Di\cdo=
t i=3D-1.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/069c3dd493e19b20ac7880df02ad351dfdcc4251" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.505ex; width:14.955ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle i^=
{2}=3Di\cdot i=3D-1.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>This formula distinguishes the complex number <i>i</i> from any real num=
ber, since the square of any (negative or positive) real number is always a=
 non-negative real number.
</p><p>With this definition of multiplication and addition, familiar rules =
for the arithmetic of rational or real numbers continue to hold for complex=
 numbers. More precisely, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dist=
ributive_property" title=3D"Distributive property">distributive property</a=
>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commutative_property" title=
=3D"Commutative property">commutative properties</a> (of addition and multi=
plication) hold. Therefore, the complex numbers form an algebraic structure=
 known as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_(mathematics)" t=
itle=3D"Field (mathematics)"><i>field</i></a>, the same way as the rational=
 or real numbers do.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEApostol198115=E2=80=9316_11=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_nu=
mber#cite_note-FOOTNOTEApostol198115%E2%80%9316-11"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
