/wiki/Winding_number" title=3D"Winding number">winding number</a>, or a pro=
of combining <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galois_theory" title=
=3D"Galois theory">Galois theory</a> and the fact that any real polynomial =
of <i>odd</i> degree has at least one real root.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DComplex_number&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negative_number#History"=
 title=3D"Negative number">Negative number =C2=A7&nbsp;History</a></div>
<p>The solution in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nth_root" title=
=3D"Nth root">radicals</a> (without <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Trigonometric_functions" title=3D"Trigonometric functions">trigonometric =
functions</a>) of a general <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_=
equation" title=3D"Cubic equation">cubic equation</a>, when all three of it=
s roots are real numbers, contains the square roots of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negative_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Negat=
ive numbers">negative numbers</a>, a situation that cannot be rectified by =
factoring aided by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_ro=
ot_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rational root test">rational root t=
est</a>, if the cubic is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irreducib=
le_polynomial" title=3D"Irreducible polynomial">irreducible</a>; this is th=
e so-called <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casus_irreducibilis=
" title=3D"Casus irreducibilis">casus irreducibilis</a></i> ("irreducible c=
ase"). This conundrum led Italian mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Gerolamo_Cardano" title=3D"Gerolamo Cardano">Gerolamo Cardano=
</a> to conceive of complex numbers in around 1545 in his <i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ars_Magna_(Cardano_book)" title=3D"Ars Magna (Ca=
rdano book)">Ars Magna</a></i>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#cite_note-21"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> though his understanding was rudimentary; moreover, he later describ=
ed complex numbers as being "as subtle as they are useless".<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compl=
ex_number#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Cardano did use imaginary numbers, but=
 described using them as "mental torture".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#cite_not=
e-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> This was prior to the use of the graphical complex plane.=
 Cardano and other Italian mathematicians, notably <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Scipione_del_Ferro" title=3D"Scipione del Ferro">Scipione =
del Ferro</a>, in the 1500s created an algorithm for solving cubic equation=
s which generally had one real solution and two solutions containing an ima=
ginary number. Because they ignored the answers with the imaginary numbers,=
 Cardano found them useless.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#cite_note-24"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>Work on the problem of general polynomials ultimately led to the fun=
damental theorem of algebra, which shows that with complex numbers, a solut=
ion exists to every <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_equ=
ation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polynomial equation">polynomial equat=
ion</a> of degree one or higher. Complex numbers thus form an <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraically_closed_field" title=3D"Algebraica=
lly closed field">algebraically closed field</a>, where any polynomial equa=
tion has a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_of_a_function" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Root of a function">root</a>.
</p><p>Many mathematicians contributed to the development of complex number=
s. The rules for addition, subtraction, multiplication, and root extraction=
 of complex numbers were developed by the Italian mathematician <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rafael_Bombelli" title=3D"Rafael Bombelli">Ra=
fael Bombelli</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A more=
 abstract formalism for the complex numbers was further developed by the Ir=
ish mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Rowan_Ha=
milton" title=3D"William Rowan Hamilton">William Rowan Hamilton</a>, who ex=
tended this abstraction to the theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Quaternions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quaternions">quaternions=
</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The earliest fleeting reference to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Square_root" title=3D"Square root">square roots</a> of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negative_number" title=3D"Negative number">neg=
ative numbers</a> can perhaps be said to occur in the work of the Greek mat=
hematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hero_of_Alexandria" tit=
le=3D"Hero of Alexandria">Hero of Alexandria</a> in the 1st century <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AD" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"AD">AD=
</a>, where in his <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hero_of_Alex=
andria#Bibliography" title=3D"Hero of Alexandria">Stereometrica</a></i> he =
considered, apparently in error, the volume of an impossible <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frustum" title=3D"Frustum">frustum</a> of a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid" title=3D"Pyramid">pyramid</a>=
 to arrive at the term <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inl=
ine"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"d=
