c_equation" title=3D"Cubic equation">cubic</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Quartic_equation" title=3D"Quartic equation">quartic</a> <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">po=
lynomials</a> were discovered by Italian mathematicians (<a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niccol%C3%B2_Fontana_Tartaglia" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Niccol=C3=B2 Fontana Tartaglia">Niccol=C3=B2 Fontana Tartaglia</=
a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gerolamo_Cardano" title=3D"=
Gerolamo Cardano">Gerolamo Cardano</a>). It was soon realized (but proved m=
uch later)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Casus_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#cite_note-Casus-30"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 that these formulas, even if one were interested only in real solutions, s=
ometimes required the manipulation of square roots of negative numbers. In =
fact, it was proved later that the use of complex numbers <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casus_irreducibilis" title=3D"Casus irreducibilis">=
is unavoidable</a> when all three roots are real and distinct.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Com=
plex_number#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>c<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, the general formula can still=
 be used in this case, with some care to deal with the ambiguity resulting =
from the existence of three cubic roots for nonzero complex numbers. Rafael=
 Bombelli was the first to address explicitly these seemingly paradoxical s=
olutions of cubic equations and developed the rules for complex arithmetic,=
 trying to resolve these issues.
</p><p>The term "imaginary" for these quantities was coined by <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes" title=3D"Ren=C3=A9 Descar=
tes">Ren=C3=A9 Descartes</a> in 1637, who was at pains to stress their unre=
al nature:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>...&nbsp;sometimes only imaginary, t=
hat is one can imagine as many as I said in each equation, but sometimes th=
ere exists no quantity that matches that which we imagine.<br>
[<i>...&nbsp;quelquefois seulement imaginaires c'est-=C3=A0-dire que l'on p=
eut toujours en imaginer autant que j'ai dit en chaque =C3=A9quation, mais =
qu'il n'y a quelquefois aucune quantit=C3=A9 qui corresponde =C3=A0 celle q=
u'on imagine.</i>]</p></blockquote>
