</p><p>by formally manipulating complex <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Power_series" title=3D"Power series">power series</a> and observed th=
at this formula could be used to reduce any trigonometric identity to much =
simpler exponential identities.
</p><p>The idea of a complex number as a point in the complex plane was fir=
st described by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denmark" title=3D"=
Denmark">Danish</a>=E2=80=93<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norway=
" title=3D"Norway">Norwegian</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
athematician" title=3D"Mathematician">mathematician</a> <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caspar_Wessel" title=3D"Caspar Wessel">Caspar Wessel<=
/a> in 1799,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> although it =
had been anticipated as early as 1685 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/John_Wallis" title=3D"John Wallis">Wallis's</a> <i>A Treatise of Alg=
ebra</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Wessel's memoir appeared in the Proceedings of the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Copenhagen_Academy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Copenhagen Academy">Copenhagen Academy</a> but went largely unnoticed. In 1=
806 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Robert_Argand" title=3D"J=
ean-Robert Argand">Jean-Robert Argand</a> independently issued a pamphlet o=
n complex numbers and provided a rigorous proof of the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_algebra#History" title=3D"Funda=
mental theorem of algebra">fundamental theorem of algebra</a>.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Com=
plex_number#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Carl Friedrich Gauss">Carl Friedrich Gau=
ss</a> had earlier published an essentially <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Topology" title=3D"Topology">topological</a> proof of the theorem=
 in 1797 but expressed his doubts at the time about "the true metaphysics o=
f the square root of =E2=88=921".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#cite_note-39"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> It was not until 1831 that he overcame these doubts and published =
his treatise on complex numbers as points in the plane,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Ewald_40-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Co=
mplex_number#cite_note-Ewald-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> largely establishing modern no=
tation and terminology:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGauss1831_41-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#cite_no=
te-FOOTNOTEGauss1831-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote><p>If one formerly contemplated this subject from a false point=
 of view and therefore found a mysterious darkness, this is in large part a=
ttributable to clumsy terminology. Had one not called +1, =E2=88=921, <span=
