=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The English mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
.H._Hardy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"G.H. Hardy">G.H. Hardy</a> remark=
ed that Gauss was the first mathematician to use complex numbers in "a real=
ly confident and scientific way" although mathematicians such as Norwegian =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niels_Henrik_Abel" title=3D"Niels =
Henrik Abel">Niels Henrik Abel</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Carl_Gustav_Jacob_Jacobi" title=3D"Carl Gustav Jacob Jacobi">Carl Gust=
av Jacob Jacobi</a> were necessarily using them routinely before Gauss publ=
ished his 1831 treatise.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#cite_note-50"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augustin-Louis_Cauchy" titl=
e=3D"Augustin-Louis Cauchy">Augustin-Louis Cauchy</a> and <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernhard_Riemann" title=3D"Bernhard Riemann">Bernha=
rd Riemann</a> together brought the fundamental ideas of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#Complex_analysis">complex analysis</a=
> to a high state of completion, commencing around 1825 in Cauchy's case.
</p><p>The common terms used in the theory are chiefly due to the founders.=
 Argand called <span class=3D"texhtml">cos <i>=CF=86</i> + <i>i</i> sin <i>=
