ontinuous functions</a> in (real) analysis have natural analogs in complex =
analysis. A sequence  of complex numbers is said to <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Convergent_sequence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Conve=
rgent sequence">converge</a> if and only if its real and imaginary parts do=
. This is equivalent to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/(%CE%B=
5,_%CE%B4)-definition_of_limit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"(=CE=B5, =CE=
=B4)-definition of limit">(=CE=B5, =CE=B4)-definition of limits</a>, where =
the absolute value of real numbers is replaced by the one of complex number=
s. From a more abstract point of view, <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-=
math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-=
