<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Triangles">Triangles</h4><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DComplex_number&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: Triangles"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Every triangle has a unique <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ste=
iner_inellipse" title=3D"Steiner inellipse">Steiner inellipse</a> =E2=80=93=
 an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipse" title=3D"Ellipse">ell=
ipse</a> inside the triangle and tangent to the midpoints of the three side=
s of the triangle. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Focus_(geom=
etry)" title=3D"Focus (geometry)">foci</a> of a triangle's Steiner inellips=
e can be found as follows, according to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Marden%27s_theorem" title=3D"Marden's theorem">Marden's theorem</a>:<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-64" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Complex_number#cite_note-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-65" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number#c=
ite_note-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> Denote the triangle's vertices in the complex plan=
e as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =3D <i>x</i><sub><i>A</i></sub> + <i>=
y</i><sub><i>A</i></sub><i>i</i></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> =
=3D <i>x</i><sub><i>B</i></sub> + <i>y</i><sub><i>B</i></sub><i>i</i></span=
>, and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i> =3D <i>x</i><sub><i>C</i></sub> + <=
i>y</i><sub><i>C</i></sub><i>i</i></span>. Write the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_equation" title=3D"Cubic equation">cubic equation<=
/a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D=
"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><mat=
h xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle (x=
-a)(x-b)(x-c)=3D0}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>c</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>0</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle (x-a)(x-b)(x-=
c)=3D0}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/1856f8d9b149522168258a0bde389d0a53e9c6b1" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:25.433ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle (x=
-a)(x-b)(x-c)=3D0}"></span>, take its derivative, and equate the (quadratic=
) derivative to zero. Marden's theorem says that the solutions of this equa=
tion are the complex numbers denoting the locations of the two foci of the =
Steiner inellipse.
</p>
