<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Analytic_number_theory">Ana=
lytic number theory</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DComplex_number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Analytic number theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_number_theo=
ry" title=3D"Analytic number theory">Analytic number theory</a></div>
<p>Analytic number theory studies numbers, often integers or rationals, by =
taking advantage of the fact that they can be regarded as complex numbers, =
in which analytic methods can be used. This is done by encoding number-theo=
retic information in complex-valued functions. For example, the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemann_zeta_function" title=3D"Riemann zeta =
function">Riemann zeta function</a> <span class=3D"texhtml">=CE=B6(<i>s</i>=
)</span> is related to the distribution of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number">prime numbers</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Improper_integrals">Imprope=
r integrals</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Complex_number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: I=
mproper integrals"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<p>In applied fields, complex numbers are often used to compute certain rea=
l-valued <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Improper_integral" title=
=3D"Improper integral">improper integrals</a>, by means of complex-valued f=
unctions. Several methods exist to do this; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Methods_of_contour_integration" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Methods of contour integration">methods of contour integration</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Dynamic_equations">Dynamic =
equations</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCo=
mplex_number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Dyn=
amic equations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_equation" title=
=3D"Differential equation">differential equations</a>, it is common to firs=
t find all complex roots <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">r</span> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_dif=
ferential_equation#Homogeneous_equation_with_constant_coefficients" title=
=3D"Linear differential equation">characteristic equation</a> of a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_differential_equation" title=3D"Li=
near differential equation">linear differential equation</a> or equation sy=
stem and then attempt to solve the system in terms of base functions of the=
 form <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>t</i>) =3D <i>e</i><sup><i>rt</i>=
</sup></span>. Likewise, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differ=
ence_equations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Difference equations">differ=
ence equations</a>, the complex roots <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">r</span> of the characteristic equation of the differe=
nce equation system are used, to attempt to solve the system in terms of ba=
se functions of the form <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>t</i>) =3D <i>=
r</i><sup><i>t</i></sup></span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Linear_algebra">Linear alge=
bra</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DComplex_=
number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: Linear al=
gebra"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<p>Since <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span cla=
ss=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"=
><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaysty=
le \mathbb {C} }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"double-struck">C</mi>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathbb {C} }=
</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/f9add4085095b9b6d28d045fd9c92c2c09f549a7" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.678ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \ma=
thbb {C} }"></span> is algebraically closed, any non-empty complex <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_matrix" title=3D"Square matrix">sq=
uare matrix</a> has at least one (complex) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Eigenvalue" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Eigenvalue">eigenvalue<=
/a>. By comparison, real matrices do not always have real eigenvalues, for =
example <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotation_matrix" title=3D"=
Rotation matrix">rotation matrices</a> (for rotations of the plane for angl=
es other than 0=C2=B0 or 180=C2=B0) leave no direction fixed, and therefore=
 do not have any <i>real</i> eigenvalue. The existence of (complex) eigenva=
lues, and the ensuing existence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Eigendecomposition_of_a_matrix" title=3D"Eigendecomposition of a matrix">e=
igendecomposition</a> is a useful tool for computing matrix powers and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_exponential" title=3D"Matrix ex=
ponential">matrix exponentials</a>.=20
</p><p>Complex numbers often generalize concepts originally conceived in th=
e real numbers. For example, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
onjugate_transpose" title=3D"Conjugate transpose">conjugate transpose</a> g=
eneralizes the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transpose" title=3D=
"Transpose">transpose</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermiti=
an_matrix" title=3D"Hermitian matrix">hermitian matrices</a> generalize <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetric_matrix" title=3D"Symmetric =
matrix">symmetric matrices</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Unitary_matrix" title=3D"Unitary matrix">unitary matrices</a> generalize =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal_matrix" title=3D"Orthog=
onal matrix">orthogonal matrices</a>.
</p>
