1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_plane#Use_in_con=
trol_theory" title=3D"Complex plane">Complex plane =C2=A7&nbsp;Use in contr=
ol theory</a></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control_theory" title=3D"Con=
trol theory">control theory</a>, systems are often transformed from the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_domain" title=3D"Time domain">ti=
me domain</a> to the complex <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequ=
ency_domain" title=3D"Frequency domain">frequency domain</a> using the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_transform" title=3D"Laplace tr=
ansform">Laplace transform</a>. The system's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Zeros_and_poles" title=3D"Zeros and poles">zeros and poles</a> a=
re then analyzed in the <i>complex plane</i>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Root_locus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Root locus">root=
 locus</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nyquist_plot" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Nyquist plot">Nyquist plot</a>, and <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nichols_plot" title=3D"Nichols plot">Nichols plot<=
/a> techniques all make use of the complex plane.
</p><p>In the root locus method, it is important whether zeros and poles ar=
e in the left or right half planes, that is, have real part greater than or=
 less than zero. If a linear, time-invariant (LTI) system has poles that ar=
e
</p>
<ul><li>in the right half plane, it will be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Unstable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Unstable">unstable</a>,<=
/li>
<li>all in the left half plane, it will be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/BIBO_stability" title=3D"BIBO stability">stable</a>,</li>
<li>on the imaginary axis, it will have <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Marginal_stability" title=3D"Marginal stability">marginal stability</=
a>.</li></ul>
<p>If a system has zeros in the right half plane, it is a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nonminimum_phase" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"No=
nminimum phase">nonminimum phase</a> system.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Signal_analysis">Signal ana=
lysis</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DComple=
x_number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Signal =
analysis"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<p>Complex numbers are used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sig=
nal_analysis" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Signal analysis">signal analys=
is</a> and other fields for a convenient description for periodically varyi=
ng signals. For given real functions representing actual physical quantitie=
s, often in terms of sines and cosines, corresponding complex functions are=
 considered of which the real parts are the original quantities. For a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sine_wave" title=3D"Sine wave">sine wa=
ve</a> of a given <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequency" title=
=3D"Frequency">frequency</a>, the absolute value <span class=3D"texhtml">|<=
i>z</i>|</span> of the corresponding <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">z</span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Amplitude" title=3D"Amplitude">amplitude</a> and the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argument_(complex_analysis)" title=3D"Argument (comple=
x analysis)">argument</a> <span class=3D"texhtml">arg <i>z</i></span> is th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phase_(waves)" title=3D"Phase (w=
aves)">phase</a>.
</p><p>If <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier_analysis" title=
=3D"Fourier analysis">Fourier analysis</a> is employed to write a given rea=
l-valued signal as a sum of periodic functions, these periodic functions ar=
e often written as complex-valued functions of the form
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
