<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Electromagnetism_and_electr=
ical_engineering">Electromagnetism and electrical engineering</h4><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DComplex_number&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" title=3D"Edit section: Electromagnetism and elect=
rical engineering"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alternating_current"=
 title=3D"Alternating current">Alternating current</a></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_engineering" titl=
e=3D"Electrical engineering">electrical engineering</a>, the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier_transform" title=3D"Fourier transform">F=
ourier transform</a> is used to analyze varying <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Electric_current" title=3D"Electric current">electric current=
s</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voltage" title=3D"Voltag=
e">voltages</a>. The treatment of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Resistor" title=3D"Resistor">resistors</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Capacitor" title=3D"Capacitor">capacitors</a>, and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inductor" title=3D"Inductor">inductors</a> can t=
hen be unified by introducing imaginary, frequency-dependent resistances fo=
r the latter two and combining all three in a single complex number called =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_impedance" title=3D=
"Electrical impedance">impedance</a>. This approach is called <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phasor" title=3D"Phasor">phasor</a> calculus.
</p><p>In electrical engineering, the imaginary unit is denoted by <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">j</span>, to avoid confus=
ion with <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">I</span>=
, which is generally in use to denote electric current, or, more particular=
