<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Fluid_dynamics">Fluid dynam=
ics</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DComplex_=
number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D33" title=3D"Edit section: Fluid dyn=
amics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_dynamics" title=3D"Flu=
id dynamics">fluid dynamics</a>, complex functions are used to describe <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Potential_flow_in_two_dimensions" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Potential flow in two dimensions">potential flo=
w in two dimensions</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Quantum_mechanics">Quantum =
mechanics</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCo=
mplex_number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D34" title=3D"Edit section: Qua=
ntum mechanics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>The complex number field is intrinsic to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Mathematical_formulations_of_quantum_mechanics" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Mathematical formulations of quantum mechanics">mathemati=
cal formulations of quantum mechanics</a>, where complex <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert_space" title=3D"Hilbert space">Hilbert space=
s</a> provide the context for one such formulation that is convenient and p=
erhaps most standard. The original foundation formulas of quantum mechanics=
 =E2=80=93 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schr%C3%B6dinger_eq=
uation" title=3D"Schr=C3=B6dinger equation">Schr=C3=B6dinger equation</a> a=
nd Heisenberg's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_mechanics" =
title=3D"Matrix mechanics">matrix mechanics</a> =E2=80=93 make use of compl=
ex numbers.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Relativity">Relativity</h4>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DComplex_number&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D35" title=3D"Edit section: Relativity"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_relativity" title=3D=
"Special relativity">special relativity</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/General_relativity" title=3D"General relativity">general rela=
tivity</a>, some formulas for the metric on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Spacetime" title=3D"Spacetime">spacetime</a> become simpler if on=
e takes the time component of the spacetime continuum to be imaginary. (Thi=
s approach is no longer standard in classical relativity, but is <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wick_rotation" title=3D"Wick rotation">used =
in an essential way</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum=
_field_theory" title=3D"Quantum field theory">quantum field theory</a>.) Co=
mplex numbers are essential to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spi=
nor" title=3D"Spinor">spinors</a>, which are a generalization of the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tensor" title=3D"Tensor">tensors</a> use=
d in relativity.
</p>
